<br>  Hello Bhaskar Chowdhury,<br>

Imagine you work in a big distributed team.
There's a huge codebase.

Sometimes you get stuck, with a piece of code that you don't
quite understand.

You'd like to ask someone in your team to help you.
But who would be the right person to ask?

Here's one idea.
The following line in your .vimrc file:

map :!git shortlog -s -n %

would let you perform the "git shortlog" analysis on Vim's
current opened file (in this case, mapped to F2).
The output is a list of every git user that changed the file,
sorted by the commit count.

Btw, git shortlog is a nice way to summarize the git log output
(more info: https://git-scm.com/docs/git-shortlog (
https://el2.convertkit-mail.com/c/wvu869rlgva6u34zl2h7/08hwh9hv9287k/aHR0cH=
M6Ly9naXQtc2NtLmNvbS9kb2NzL2dpdC1zaG9ydGxvZw=3D=3D )).
Thanks Davi Marcondes Moreira for sharing this idea!

Cheers,
Jovica

---

P.S.
Some of my best readers come from people just like you
Bhaskar Chowdhury. People who are kind and
helpful and with whom we could share a coffee/beer/etc.

I would love to have a few more people join us on this MVQ
journey.
It would really be nice if you could tell just one friend about
this newsletter.
E-mail works best - so if you can, please send an e-mail one
friend or colleague of yours.

Here's a sample text you can use:

---
Hey,

You might like this newsletter on Vim: https://masteringvim.com,
( https://el2.convertkit-mail.com/c/wvu869rlgva6u34zl2h7/4zuvhehvpmo05/aHR0=
cHM6Ly9tYXN0ZXJpbmd2aW0uY29t )It's pretty cool, and it gets
published every week, by the author of Mastering Vim Quickly (
https://el2.convertkit-mail.com/c/wvu869rlgva6u34zl2h7/78i7h8hq69g07/aHR0cH=
M6Ly9qb3ZpY2FpbGljLm9yZy9tYXN0ZXJpbmctdmltLXF1aWNrbHkv ) book.

Cheers!
---

